Not unused. Uninitialized.<p>E.g. in older GCC you would get 
int x;
switch (!!foo) {
  case 0:x=0;break;
  case 1:x=1;break;
  /<i>no default</i>/
}
print(..x)<p>Or many other cases and the compiler will give an erroneous uninitialized warning. you can assign x to itself at the stop to eliminate the warning without changing the generated code.
